{{For|the album|Love-In}} {{refimprove|date=October 2008}} A '''love-in''' is a peaceful public gathering focused on [[meditation]], [[love]], [[music]], [[human sexual behavior|sex]] and/or use of [[psychedelic drug]]s. The term was coined by Los Angeles radio comedian [[Peter Bergman (comedian)|Peter Bergman]], who also hosted the first one in March or April 1967 (sources disagree) in [[Elysian Park]].<ref>[http://losangelesfreepress.com/the-impossible-come-back-of-radio-free-oz/]{{dead link|date=January 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }} The impossible come-back of Radio Free Oz</ref><ref>[http://www.firesigntheatre.com/albums/bergman.html] Peter Bergman biography</ref> It has been interpreted in different ways by different organizations, but is often connected to [[civil disobedience|protest]]ing local, social or [[Environmental movement|environmental]] issues.<ref> [http://www.bookoflife.org/history/usa/GUS06.htm Book of Life] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170103001341/http://bookoflife.org/history/usa/GUS06.htm |date=2017-01-03 }} reference to early love-ins</ref><ref>A [[Houston]]-area "[http://ultimateheights.com/stories/236393-love-in-protest-today-seeks-to-save-love-elementary Love In] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110312100328/http://ultimateheights.com/stories/236393-love-in-protest-today-seeks-to-save-love-elementary |date=2011-03-12 }}" -- a flash mob gathering to save Love Elementary School from being shut down, in March 2011.</ref> Such protests were held in opposition to the [[Vietnam War]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://history.sandiego.edu/gen/qt/v/19670505a.html |title=Newsreel |publisher=History.sandiego.edu |date= |accessdate=2010-09-01}}</ref>
Love-ins are largely considered a staple of the 1960s [[counterculture]] [[hippie]] culture.
