'''Museum fatigue''' is a state of physical or mental [[Fatigue (medical)|fatigue]] caused by the experience of exhibits in [[museum]]s and similar cultural institutions. The collection of phenomena that characterize museum fatigue was first described in 1916,<ref name="gilman1916">{{cite journal|last1=Gilman|first1=Benjamin Ives|title=Museum Fatigue|journal=The Scientific Monthly|date=1916|volume=2|issue=1|pages=62–74|jstor=6127}}</ref> and has since received widespread attention in popular and scientific contexts.<ref name="bitgood2009">{{cite journal|last1=Bitgood|first1=Stephen|title=Museum Fatigue: A Critical Review|journal=Visitor Studies|date=2009|volume=12|issue=2|pages=93–111|doi=10.1080/10645570903203406}}</ref><ref name="adams2009">{{cite news|last1=Adams|first1=Stephen|title=Ashmolean Museum redesigned to combat 'museum fatigue'|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/culturenews/6453817/Ashmolean-Museum-redesigned-to-combat-museum-fatigue.html|accessdate=29 May 2017|work=The Telegraph|date=2009}}</ref><ref name="lonelyplanet">{{cite web|title=Enough with the ‘Wow!’ already! How to avoid museum fatigue.|url=http://www.lonelyplanet.com/blog/2011/02/03/enough-with-the-wow-already-how-to-avoid-museum-fatigue/|publisher=Lonely Planet|accessdate=29 May 2017}}</ref>

